intro: Botrychium australe var. millefolium, commonly known as the Australian moonwort, is a fern-like plant native to Australia. It belongs to the family Osmundaceae and is characterized by its distinctive, fan-shaped fronds. The plant has a unique reproductive structure called a sorus, which contains the spore-producing organs. It typically grows in moist, shaded environments such as forests and rocky areas. Its botanical features make it an interesting subject for studies in plant morphology and ecology.
